TIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF002181%2F1"><gtr:id>FF8B4FED-7C3F-4324-9B98-DF16F935CD18</gtr:id><gtr:title>Household financial management and its interests for intra-familial relations: Adopting a cross cultural and cross disciplinary approach</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F002181/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Knowing how a couple manages their money is important not just from an academic perspective, but because martial law and public policy are based on certain expectations about household financial practices. Through a series of methodologically diverse studies, the thesis provides the first detailed analysis of the money management of unmarried heterosexual cohabitants in the UK. The findings of interview and survey studies indicate that although there was a high level of separate money management, exploring the meanings and practices behind separate arrangements revealed a more complex picture. In terms of legal and policy implications, the findings indicate that the use of separate accounts should not be taken as evidence that a couple are operating as separate financial entities. Rather it is important to take account of how the couple perceive the ownership of money and the reasons behind their arrangements. The findings also underline the need to take account of the diversity of couples included under the umbrella heading of cohabitation, and to exercise caution when comparing cohabiting and married couples as general groups. Interview findings indicate that cohabitation should be viewed as a dynamic relationship, with potential for change over time in the meaning of the relationship. 
